24
00:00:52,980 --> 00:00:55,550
At the 2019 Oslo Freedom Forum,

25
00:00:55,550 --> 00:00:58,270
Shelley Zhang had the chance to sit down with
Esther Htusan.

26
00:00:58,270 --> 00:01:00,920
She’s a Pulitzer Prize winning Burmese journalist.

27
00:01:00,920 --> 00:01:03,320
And she shares with us what China’s influence

28
00:01:03,320 --> 00:01:06,310
is doing to her country.

29
00:01:06,310 --> 00:01:07,920
Thanks for joining us today, Esther.

30
00:01:07,920 --> 00:01:09,060
Thanks for having me.

31
00:01:09,060 --> 00:01:11,100
So how would you describe the relationship

32
00:01:11,100 --> 00:01:12,950
between Burma and China?

33
00:01:12,950 --> 00:01:16,659
Well, Burma had been under the military dictatorship

34
00:01:16,659 --> 00:01:19,609
for about half a century

35
00:01:19,609 --> 00:01:25,640
and during that period,

36
00:01:25,640 --> 00:01:28,590
it was isolated from the rest of the world,

37
00:01:28,590 --> 00:01:37,479
especially the western country.

38
00:01:37,479 --> 00:01:42,620
China is one of the main country that support
Burma

39
00:01:42,620 --> 00:01:46,850
so they had a very long, close relationship

40
00:01:46,850 --> 00:01:51,189
between the two countries and China

41
00:01:51,189 --> 00:01:54,820
was a long time investor in the country

42
00:01:54,820 --> 00:01:56,539
when the rest of the world

43
00:01:56,539 --> 00:01:57,881
would not even enter Burma,

44
00:01:57,881 --> 00:02:01,840
so they do have this love and hate relationship

45
00:02:01,840 --> 00:02:07,170
because sometimes the political conflicts
with China.

46
00:02:07,170 --> 00:02:10,880
Then sometimes Burma has only China as the
only country

47
00:02:10,880 --> 00:02:13,160
that they can rely on so there is this,

48
00:02:13,160 --> 00:02:16,510
I would say it's a very close relationship

49
00:02:16,510 --> 00:02:19,950
that has been a long standing with China.

50
00:02:19,950 --> 00:02:27,080
There is some tension there, is what you're
saying?

51
00:02:27,080 --> 00:02:31,720
Yeah, there were times when Burma felt like
China

52
00:02:31,720 --> 00:02:33,940
was bullying them because they had no other
country

53
00:02:33,940 --> 00:02:37,960
to rely on so there is some tension coming
up

54
00:02:37,960 --> 00:02:40,330
and then it will ease again when China

55
00:02:40,330 --> 00:02:43,080
had a better investment plan inside Burma

56
00:02:43,080 --> 00:02:47,350
so it's just this on and off, love and hate
relationship.

57
00:02:47,350 --> 00:02:49,370
So one of the things that might be

58
00:02:49,370 --> 00:02:51,550
a little bit of a source of tension

59
00:02:51,550 --> 00:02:54,380
is human trafficking in Burma, right?

60
00:02:54,380 --> 00:02:58,590
The one child policy in China has left a lot
of extra men

61
00:02:58,590 --> 00:03:02,440
who can't get wives and that's led to some
trafficking,

62
00:03:02,440 --> 00:03:04,930
sex trafficking of women from Southeast Asia.

63
00:03:04,930 --> 00:03:09,740
Is this something that's affecting Burmese
women too?

64
00:03:09,740 --> 00:03:12,130
Absolutely.

65
00:03:12,130 --> 00:03:13,150
Over the years there are just hundreds

66
00:03:13,150 --> 00:03:16,660
of thousands of women who have been trafficked
inside of Burma

67
00:03:16,660 --> 00:03:23,500
and then sold as brides in China and it has
become a very lucrative,

68
00:03:23,500 --> 00:03:27,230
illicit trade cross border.

69
00:03:27,230 --> 00:03:28,720
Not only just Burma but also

70
00:03:28,720 --> 00:03:33,820
other Southeast Asian nations that border
with China.

71
00:03:33,820 --> 00:03:39,480
So the biggest problem is that China initiated
this one child policy

72
00:03:39,480 --> 00:03:44,160
a long time ago and to balance out their male
and female population,

73
00:03:44,160 --> 00:03:50,640
it is going to take a long time because they
did it for so long

74
00:03:50,640 --> 00:03:53,250
that they have imbalanced women.

75
00:03:53,250 --> 00:03:57,650
There's something like thirty million more
Chinese men.

76
00:03:57,650 --> 00:04:01,200
Exactly so they need more women for those
men to get married

77
00:04:01,200 --> 00:04:04,990
because they don't have enough women so what
happens

78
00:04:04,990 --> 00:04:09,670
is mostly Southeast Asian countries,

79
00:04:09,670 --> 00:04:14,920
particularly the more poorer area that is
bordering China

80
00:04:14,920 --> 00:04:16,049
like Burma for example,

81
00:04:16,049 --> 00:04:18,539
Northern and Northeast Burma,

82
00:04:18,539 --> 00:04:21,979
many women along this border have been trafficked
for many times

83
00:04:21,979 --> 00:04:26,729
for example I did a few investigative stories
about women

84
00:04:26,729 --> 00:04:30,050
who had been affected by Burma's internal
conflict

85
00:04:30,050 --> 00:04:33,610
and then they were fleeing closer to China
border

86
00:04:33,610 --> 00:04:38,850
and ended up getting trafficked and sold as
brides in China.

87
00:04:38,850 --> 00:04:45,810
So it is a very regular incidence and it is
a very big issue

88
00:04:45,810 --> 00:04:47,250
inside Burma at the moment.

89
00:04:47,250 --> 00:04:49,449
So you said hundreds of thousands of women?

90
00:04:49,449 --> 00:04:50,490
Over the years, right.

91
00:04:50,490 --> 00:04:52,969
So is this something the Burmese government
is talking about

92
00:04:52,969 --> 00:04:56,599
or is it more off-limits because it has to
do with China?

93
00:04:56,599 --> 00:04:59,680
So when it come to human trafficking issue,

94
00:04:59,680 --> 00:05:04,129
it is less political so there are things that
the Burmese authorities

95
00:05:04,129 --> 00:05:10,370
try to stop but the problem with Burma is
the rule of law.

96
00:05:10,370 --> 00:05:14,080
It has a very weak implementation of rule
of law

97
00:05:14,080 --> 00:05:17,219
and particularly along the border region

98
00:05:17,219 --> 00:05:23,539
there's no influence of legal protections

99
00:05:23,539 --> 00:05:27,779
or there's no control over by the central
government

100
00:05:27,779 --> 00:05:31,660
along the border so it's more difficult

101
00:05:31,660 --> 00:05:35,240
for the government to implement trying to
stop human trafficking

102
00:05:35,240 --> 00:05:42,099
or also the Burmese government has long been
famous for incompetence

103
00:05:42,099 --> 00:05:46,699
to actually try to stop this kind of issue
so it's still ongoing.

104
00:05:46,699 --> 00:05:48,460
They seem to be doing better job trying

105
00:05:48,460 --> 00:05:51,080
to stop this kind of human trafficking

106
00:05:51,080 --> 00:05:54,629
or even trying to get involved in going to
rescue women

107
00:05:54,629 --> 00:05:57,460
who had already been trafficked

108
00:05:57,460 --> 00:06:02,319
but the problem is the Burmese government
is not that willing

109
00:06:02,319 --> 00:06:09,159
to really use the man power to rescue these
women

110
00:06:09,159 --> 00:06:14,689
or to actually stop this issue because to
me as a journalist

111
00:06:14,689 --> 00:06:19,400
it seems like the authorities don't really
care.

112
00:06:19,400 --> 00:06:21,660
Is there a way for these Burmese women

113
00:06:21,660 --> 00:06:24,320
to escape once they get to China?

114
00:06:24,320 --> 00:06:26,099
Can they get back?

115
00:06:26,099 --> 00:06:29,439
So we have women organizations inside

116
00:06:29,439 --> 00:06:32,419
and also along the border of China

117
00:06:32,419 --> 00:06:34,300
and these women organizations are amazing.

118
00:06:34,300 --> 00:06:39,650
They are doing a great job.

119
00:06:39,650 --> 00:06:42,539
They actually sent out people who can rescue
these women

120
00:06:42,539 --> 00:06:45,340
in the middle of nowhere inside China.

121
00:06:45,340 --> 00:06:47,500
It could take days, it could take months,

122
00:06:47,500 --> 00:06:50,439
sometimes it take year but they don't give
up.

123
00:06:50,439 --> 00:06:52,979
They actually go and try to rescue.

124
00:06:52,979 --> 00:06:55,699
That's amazing that they can get these women
out.

125
00:06:55,699 --> 00:06:56,699
Sure.

126
00:06:56,699 --> 00:06:59,050
So we were talking about border issues with
Burma

127
00:06:59,050 --> 00:07:04,129
and China and Burma shares a pretty substantial
border with China.

128
00:07:04,129 --> 00:07:08,419
And you talked a little bit about people fleeing
conflicts.

129
00:07:08,419 --> 00:07:10,389
Are there Burmese refugees that go into China

130
00:07:10,389 --> 00:07:13,139
and how does China deal with that issue?

131
00:07:13,139 --> 00:07:18,339
So as you said there's a substantial border
sharing

132
00:07:18,339 --> 00:07:20,379
along Burma and China

133
00:07:20,379 --> 00:07:24,009
and it is mostly in the East and Northeast
of Burma

134
00:07:24,009 --> 00:07:27,880
and along this border we have ethnic conflict

135
00:07:27,880 --> 00:07:30,770
that's ongoing for decades.

136
00:07:30,770 --> 00:07:35,279
It's been ongoing along the border where ethnic
minority groups

137
00:07:35,279 --> 00:07:37,360
have been fighting against the central government

138
00:07:37,360 --> 00:07:41,339
for indigenous rights and self-determination.

139
00:07:41,339 --> 00:07:48,620
Even since right after British Colonialism.

140
00:07:48,620 --> 00:07:53,249
And China of course when there's conflict
along the border,

141
00:07:53,249 --> 00:07:59,479
it produced quite an incredible number of
refugees.

142
00:07:59,479 --> 00:08:01,089
Many people fleeing from conflict

143
00:08:01,089 --> 00:08:04,439
and for many civilians along the border,

144
00:08:04,439 --> 00:08:06,710
they don't feel safe to run into

145
00:08:06,710 --> 00:08:08,939
the Burmese government controlled area.

146
00:08:08,939 --> 00:08:13,029
For them, they rather flee into China

147
00:08:13,029 --> 00:08:15,749
so most of them crossed into China.

148
00:08:15,749 --> 00:08:18,009
But as far as I have seen.

149
00:08:18,009 --> 00:08:22,569
The Chinese government had not done a more
sympathetic job.

150
00:08:22,569 --> 00:08:28,529
Most of them are chased away by the Chinese
soldiers back to Burma

151
00:08:28,529 --> 00:08:30,789
where they are airstrike bombing

152
00:08:30,789 --> 00:08:35,760
or there are still active conflict ongoing

153
00:08:35,760 --> 00:08:40,380
so they don't seem to have really sympathetic...

154
00:08:40,380 --> 00:08:42,430
So they don't really seem to treat them as
refugees, basically?

155
00:08:42,430 --> 00:08:43,430
No.

156
00:08:43,430 --> 00:08:44,920
Because according to the U.N. charter

157
00:08:44,920 --> 00:08:47,070
they should be accepting refugees.

158
00:08:47,070 --> 00:08:48,070
Right.

159
00:08:48,070 --> 00:08:51,060
So most of the displaced people

160
00:08:51,060 --> 00:08:55,540
or people running as refugees are sent back
to Burma.

161
00:08:55,540 --> 00:09:00,029
I read something about China actually supporting
militias

162
